      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "James, please don't apologize. It takes real courage to say what you just said, and I'm glad you told me.\n\nWhat you're describing — pushing through pain, stopping halfway, watching it get worse — that sounds genuinely hard, both physically and emotionally. The fact that embarrassment was part of it makes complete sense. A lot of runners feel like stopping or admitting something hurts means they've failed somehow. You haven't. You're here, being honest, and that's exactly the right move.\n\nI do need to be straight with you about one thing, though: diagnosing what's happening with your foot and telling you how to treat it is outside what I can do as a coach. I'm not a medical professional, and plantar fasciitis that's been aggravated — especially to the point where you're stopping runs — really needs eyes from someone qualified. That means going back to your physiotherapist, ideally soon. They've already cleared you once, and they need to know what's happened since then so they can reassess and guide your treatment.\n\n**Please reach out to your physio before your next run.** That's the most important next step right now — not a training question, a health one.\n\n---\n\nHere's what I *can* tell you, and want you to hear clearly: **nothing about this is irreversible.** You haven't blown your fitness, your goals, or this comeback. You've had a setback within a setback, and those happen. The path back still exists — it just runs through your physio's office first.\n\nOnce you have updated guidance from them, I'm ready to rebuild your plan around whatever they clear you for. Whether that's full rest, pool running, walking, or something else — we'll work with it. There's always a version of forward.\n\nCan you tell me a little more about what's been going on? What do you think has been making it hard to say the pain was getting worse?"
        }
      ],
      "messageId": "msg_017V49dVgw6mGrP3k6t5Jg6m"
    }
  ],
